Abstract The Distributed Fault-Tolerant CI/CD Workflow Execution Engine is a microservices-based system designed to execute dynamic, DAG-based CI/CD pipelines in a scalable and resilient manner
. The system allows users to submit workflows describing a sequence of tasks—such as repository cloning, code compilation, testing, and report generation—along with their dependencies
. Instead of hardcoding pipeline logic, workflows are defined dynamically and processed through an event-driven architecture that enables flexible scheduling and parallel execution
.
The platform consists of multiple loosely coupled services including a Workflow API Service, Orchestrator Service, and Worker Service, which communicate asynchronously using Apache Kafka as the event backbone
. Workflow definitions and execution states are persisted in PostgreSQL, ensuring durability and enabling recovery in case of failures
. The Orchestrator service acts as the central scheduling component, interpreting the directed acyclic graph (DAG) of tasks, determining execution order, and dispatching runnable tasks to workers through Kafka topics
.
Worker services form a scalable execution layer responsible for running real CI/CD operations using system commands
. Each worker processes tasks concurrently using a thread pool to maximize resource utilization
. The architecture incorporates a self-healing mechanism at the application level that detects stalled or failed tasks, retries execution when appropriate, and prevents duplicate processing through idempotent task handling
. Additionally, Kubernetes is used for container orchestration to provide automatic pod restarts, horizontal scaling of workers, and high availability
.
System Vision and capabilities This system resembles enterprise distributed compute engines like Apache Airflow, Netflix Conductor, and Uber Cadence
. It is not a simple script runner; it handles true distributed systems challenges including graph scheduling, back-pressure management, exactly-once mitigation, and infrastructure plus application resilience

